SIMPLE: open
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Open
<hw>O"pen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>open</ets>;
akin to D. <ets>open</ets>, OS. <ets>opan</ets>, G. <ets>offan</ets>,
Icel. <ets>opinn</ets>, Sw. <ets>⟦oum⟧ppen</ets>, Dan. <ets>aaben</ets>,
and perh. to E. <ets>up</ets>. Cf. <er>Up</er>, and <er>Ope</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Free of access; not shut up; not closed; affording
unobstructed ingress or egress; not impeding or preventing passage; not
locked up or covered over; -- applied to passageways; <as>as, an
<ex>open</ex> door, window, road, etc.</as>; also, to inclosed
structures or objects; <as>as, <ex>open</ex> houses, boxes, baskets,
bottles, etc.</as>; also, to means of communication or approach by water
or land; <as>as, an <ex>open</ex> harbor or roadstead</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Through the gate,⟦br⟧
Wide <qex>open</qex> and unguarded, Satan passed.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>Also, figuratively, used of the ways of communication of the
mind, as by the senses; ready to hear, see, etc.; as, to keep one's eyes
and ears <xex>open</xex>.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His ears are <qex>open</qex> unto their cry.</q> <rj><qau>Ps.
xxxiv. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Free to be used, enjoyed, visited, or the like; not
private; public; unrestricted in use; <as>as, an <ex>open</ex> library,
museum, court, or other assembly</as>; liable to the approach, trespass,
or attack of any one; unprotected; exposed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If Demetrius . . . have a matter against any man, the law is
<qex>open</qex> and there are deputies.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xix.
33.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The service that I truly did his life,⟦br⟧
Hath left me <qex>open</qex> to all injuries.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Free or cleared of obstruction to progress or to
view; accessible; <as>as, an <ex>open</ex> tract; the <ex>open</ex>
sea.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not drawn together, closed, or contracted; extended;
expanded; <as>as, an <ex>open</ex> hand; <ex>open</ex> arms; an
<ex>open</ex> flower; an <ex>open</ex> prospect.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each, with <qex>open</qex> arms, embraced her chosen knight.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> Hence: <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Without reserve or false
pretense; sincere; characterized by sincerity; unfeigned; frank; also,
generous; liberal; bounteous; -- applied to personal appearance, or
character, and to the expression of thought and feeling, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With aspect <qex>open</qex>, shall erect his head.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Moor is of a free and <qex>open</qex> nature.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The French are always <qex>open</qex>, familiar, and
talkative.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>Not concealed or secret; not hidden or disguised;
exposed to view or to knowledge; revealed; apparent; <as>as,
<ex>open</ex> schemes or plans; <ex>open</ex> shame or guilt;
<ex>open</ex> source code</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>His thefts are too <qex>open</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That I may find him, and with secret gaze⟦br⟧
Or <qex>open</qex> admiration him behold.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Not of a quality to prevent communication, as by
closing water ways, blocking roads, etc.; hence, not frosty or
inclement; mild; -- used of the weather or the climate; <as>as, an
<ex>open</ex> season; an <ex>open</ex> winter.</as></def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Not settled or adjusted; not decided or determined;
not closed or withdrawn from consideration; <as>as, an <ex>open</ex>
account; an <ex>open</ex> question; to keep an offer or opportunity
<ex>open</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Free; disengaged; unappropriated; <as>as, to keep a
day <ex>open</ex> for any purpose; to be <ex>open</ex> for an
engagement.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Uttered with a
relatively wide opening of the articulating organs; -- said of vowels;
<as>as, the <it>⟦aum⟧</it>n f⟦aum⟧r is <ex>open</ex> as compared with
the <it>⟦amac⟧</it> in s⟦amac⟧y</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Uttered,
as a consonant, with the oral passage simply narrowed without closure,
as in uttering <xex>s</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Not closed or
stopped with the finger; -- said of the string of an instrument, as of a
violin, when it is allowed to vibrate throughout its whole length.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Produced by an open string; <as>as, an <ex>open</ex>
tone</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>The open air</b></col>, <cd>the air out of doors.</cd> --
<col><b>Open chain</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Closed
chain</cref>, under <er>Chain</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Open
circuit</b></col> <fld>(Elec.)</fld>, <cd>a conducting circuit which is
incomplete, or interrupted at some point; -- opposed to an
uninterrupted, or <ant>closed circuit</ant>.</cd> -- <col><b>Open
communion</b></col>, <cd>communion in the Lord's supper not restricted
to persons who have been baptized by immersion. Cf. <cref>Close
communion</cref>, under <er>Close</er>, <pos>a.</pos></cd> --
<col><b>Open diapason</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>a certain stop in
an organ, in which the pipes or tubes are formed like the mouthpiece of
a flageolet at the end where the wind enters, and are open at the other
end.</cd> -- <col><b>Open flank</b></col> <fld>(Fort.)</fld>, <cd>the
part of the flank covered by the orillon.</cd> -- <col><b>Open-front
furnace</b></col> <fld>(Metal.)</fld>, <cd>a blast furnace having a
forehearth.</cd> -- <col><b>Open harmony</b></col> <fld>(Mus.)</fld>,
<cd>harmony the tones of which are widely dispersed, or separated by
wide intervals.</cd> -- <col><b>Open hawse</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>,
<cd>a hawse in which the cables are parallel or slightly divergent. Cf.
<cref>Foul hawse</cref>, under <er>Hawse</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Open
hearth</b></col> <fld>(Metal.)</fld>, <cd>the shallow hearth of a
reverberatory furnace.</cd> -- <col><b>Open-hearth furnace</b></col>,
<cd>a reverberatory furnace; esp., a kind of reverberatory furnace in
which the fuel is gas, used in manufacturing steel.</cd> --
<col><b>Open-hearth process</b></col> <fld>(Steel Manuf.)</fld>, <cd>a
process by which melted cast iron is converted into steel by the
addition of wrought iron, or iron ore and manganese, and by exposure to
heat in an open-hearth furnace; -- also called the
<altname>Siemens-Martin process</altname>, from the inventors.</cd> --
<col><b>Open-hearth steel</b></col>, <cd>steel made by an open-hearth
process; -- also called <altname>Siemens-Martin steel</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Open newel</b></col>. <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <cd>See <cref>Hollow
newel</cref>, under <er>Hollow</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Open pipe</b></col>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld>, <cd>a pipe open at the top. It has a pitch about an
octave higher than a <xex>closed pipe</xex> of the same length.</cd> --
<col><b>Open-timber roof</b></col> <fld>(Arch.)</fld>, <cd>a roof of
which the constructional parts, together with the under side of the
covering, or its lining, are treated ornamentally, and left to form the
ceiling of an apartment below, as in a church, a public hall, and the
like.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Open vowel</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>Open consonant</b></col></mcol>. <cd>See <er>Open</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>, 9.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Open</xex> is used in many compounds, most of which
are self-explaining; as, <xex>open</xex>-breasted,
<xex>open</xex>-minded.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Unclosed; uncovered; unprotected; exposed; plain;
apparent; obvious; evident; public; unreserved; frank; sincere;
undissembling; artless. See <er>Candid</er>, and
<er>Ingenuous</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Open</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Open
<hw>O"pen</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Open or unobstructed
space; clear land, without trees or obstructions; open ocean; open
water.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To sail into the <xex>open</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Jowett (Thucyd.).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then we got into the <qex>open</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W.
Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>In open</b></col>, <col><b>In th
open</b></col></mcol>, <cd>in full view; without concealment;
openly.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs> <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Open</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Open
<hw>O"pen</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Opened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Opening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>openian</ets>. See
<er>Open</er>,a.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make or set open; to render
free of access; to unclose; to unbar; to unlock; to remove any fastening
or covering from; <as>as, to <ex>open</ex> a door; to <ex>open</ex> a
box; to <ex>open</ex> a room; to <ex>open</ex> a letter.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And all the windows of my heart⟦br⟧
I <qex>open</qex> to the day.</q> <rj><qau>Whittier.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spread; to expand; <as>as, to <ex>open</ex> the
hand</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To disclose; to reveal; to interpret; to
explain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king <qex>opened</qex> himself to some of his council, that he
was sorry for the earl's death.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unto thee have I <qex>opened</qex> my cause.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. xx.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While he <qex>opened</qex> to us the Scriptures.</q> <rj><qau>Luke
xxiv. 32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make known; to discover; also, to render
available or accessible for settlements, trade, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The English did adventure far for to <qex>open</qex> the North
parts of America.</q> <rj><qau>Abp. Abbot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To enter upon; to begin; <as>as, to <ex>open</ex> a
discussion; to <ex>open</ex> fire upon an enemy; to <ex>open</ex> trade,
or correspondence; to <ex>open</ex> an investigation; to <ex>open</ex> a
case in court, or a meeting.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To loosen or make less compact; <as>as, to
<ex>open</ex> matted cotton by separating the fibers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To open one's mouth</b></col>, <col><b>to
speak</b></col></mcol>.<cd></cd> -- <col><b>To open up</b></col>, <cd>to
lay open; to discover; to disclose.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Poetry that had <qex>opened up</qex> so many delightful views into
the character and condition of our ⟦ldquo⟧bold peasantry, their
country's pride.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Prof. Wilson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Open</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Open
<hw>O"pen</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To unclose; to form a
hole, breach, or gap; to be unclosed; to be parted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The earth <qex>opened</qex> and swallowed up Dathan, and covered
the company of Abiram.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cvi. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To expand; to spread out; to be disclosed; <as>as,
the harbor <ex>opened</ex> to our view</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To begin; to commence; <as>as, the stock
<ex>opened</ex> at par; the battery <ex>opened</ex> upon the
enemy.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Sporting)</fld> <def>To bark on scent or view of
the game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Open-air</ent>⟦br⟧
